-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Acts — Part 5 (Chapters 25–28)
-- 3 difficulties × 4 chapters = 64 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 12
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 20
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 32
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 25–26 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 25 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 25, 'kids', 1, 'What did Paul say when Governor Festus asked if he wanted to go to Jerusalem for trial?', 'I appeal unto Caesar — meaning he asked to have his trial before the Roman emperor', 'I want to go to Jerusalem', 'I want to stay here in Caesarea', 'I want to go home to Tarsus', 'a', 'Acts 25:10-11 — "I stand at Caesar''s judgment seat, where I ought to be judged... I appeal unto Caesar."'),
('Acts', 25, 'kids', 2, 'What king came to visit Governor Festus in Caesarea?', 'King Agrippa and his sister Bernice', 'King Herod the Great', 'The king of Egypt', 'The emperor of Rome', 'a', 'Acts 25:13 — "And after certain days king Agrippa and Bernice came unto Caesarea to salute Festus."'),
('Acts', 25, 'kids', 3, 'What did Festus tell King Agrippa about Paul''s case?', 'The Jews had questions about their own religion and about one Jesus, who was dead, whom Paul said to be alive', 'Paul had robbed the temple', 'Paul was a dangerous criminal', 'Paul wanted to become king', 'a', 'Acts 25:19 — "But had certain questions against him of their own superstition, and of one Jesus, which was dead, whom Paul affirmed to be alive."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 25, 'teens', 1, 'Why did Paul appeal to Caesar instead of being tried in Jerusalem?', 'Paul knew the Jewish leaders wanted to ambush and kill him on the way to Jerusalem, and as a Roman citizen he had the right to be tried by the emperor himself', 'Paul wanted to see Rome as a tourist', 'Paul was afraid of Festus', 'Paul wanted to impress the other prisoners', 'a', 'Acts 25:3,9-11 — "And the Jews... laying wait in the way to kill him... Then said Paul, I stand at Caesar''s judgment seat, where I ought to be judged... I appeal unto Caesar."'),
('Acts', 25, 'teens', 2, 'What was Festus''s problem with Paul''s case?', 'He had no clear charges to write to the emperor — the accusations were about Jewish religious disputes, not Roman crimes', 'He thought Paul was guilty but could not prove it', 'He was afraid of Paul''s power', 'He did not understand Latin well enough', 'a', 'Acts 25:26-27 — "Of whom I have no certain thing to write unto my lord. Wherefore I have brought him forth before you... that, after examination had, I might have somewhat to write. For it seemeth to me unreasonable to send a prisoner, and not withal to signify the crimes laid against him."'),
('Acts', 25, 'teens', 3, 'Why did Festus want King Agrippa to hear Paul''s case?', 'Because Agrippa was an expert in Jewish customs and religion, and Festus needed help understanding the charges so he could write a report to Caesar', 'Because Agrippa was Paul''s relative', 'Because Agrippa was the emperor''s representative', 'Because Agrippa was a judge in all criminal cases', 'a', 'Acts 25:26 — "Of whom I have no certain thing to write unto my lord... I might have somewhat to write." Acts 26:3 confirms: "I know thee to be expert in all customs and questions which are among the Jews."'),
('Acts', 25, 'teens', 4, 'What did Festus say to King Agrippa about the accusations against Paul?', 'The accusers brought no charge of such things as he had expected — they had questions about their own religion and about one Jesus, who was dead, whom Paul affirmed to be alive', 'Paul was charged with murder and theft', 'The Romans accused Paul of treason', 'Paul confessed to all the charges', 'a', 'Acts 25:18-19 — "Against whom when the accusers stood up, they brought none accusation of such things as I supposed: But had certain questions against him of their own superstition, and of one Jesus, which was dead, whom Paul affirmed to be alive."'),
('Acts', 25, 'teens', 5, 'How did King Agrippa respond when Festus told him about Paul?', 'He said he would like to hear the man himself — and Festus arranged for Paul to appear before him the next day', 'He said he was not interested in the case', 'He told Festus to release Paul immediately', 'He refused to get involved in Jewish matters', 'a', 'Acts 25:22 — "Then Agrippa said unto Festus, I would also hear the man myself. To morrow, said he, thou shalt hear him."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 1, 'What does Paul''s appeal to Caesar (provocatio ad Caesarem) signify legally and theologically?', 'Legally, as a Roman citizen, Paul exercised his right to have his case heard by the emperor — removing it from provincial jurisdiction. Theologically, the appeal is the human mechanism through which God''s promise ("thou must bear witness at Rome," 23:11) is fulfilled. Paul''s legal right becomes the vehicle of divine destiny', 'The appeal was illegal for Roman citizens', 'Paul acted impulsively without divine guidance', 'The appeal delayed the gospel', 'a', 'Acts 25:11-12 — "I appeal unto Caesar. Then Festus... answered, Hast thou appealed unto Caesar? unto Caesar shalt thou go." The Lex Julia granted citizens the right of appeal. God uses Roman jurisprudence as the means to fulfil His promise: legal rights become the pathway to prophetic destiny.'),
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 2, 'What does Festus''s summary of the case ("one Jesus, which was dead, whom Paul affirmed to be alive," 25:19) reveal about how outsiders perceived the Christian message?', 'Festus distils the entire case to one question: is a dead man alive? This outsider''s summary is unintentionally accurate — the resurrection of Jesus is indeed the central issue. Festus sees it as a puzzling Jewish superstition; Luke presents it as the crux of history. The governor''s bemused incomprehension highlights the scandal of resurrection to the Gentile mind', 'Festus fully understood Christian theology', 'The resurrection was not central to the dispute', 'Festus was sympathetic to Paul''s message', 'a', 'Acts 25:19 — "One Jesus, which was dead, whom Paul affirmed to be alive." This is the entire gospel from a Roman politician''s perspective: a dead man claimed to be alive. Festus reduces the case to its essence without realising he has stated the most important claim in human history. The simplicity is devastating.'),
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 3, 'How does Festus''s dilemma (needing charges to send to Caesar) serve Luke''s apologetic purpose?', 'Festus cannot formulate charges because there are no charges — "I have no certain thing to write" (v.26). The Roman governor''s inability to identify a crime is powerful vindication: two governors (Felix and Festus) and the Sanhedrin have been unable to convict Paul of anything. Luke demonstrates that Christianity is not criminal; it is a religious dispute that Roman law should not prosecute', 'Festus was simply incompetent', 'He had clear charges but chose not to write them', 'Luke invented the dilemma', 'a', 'Acts 25:25-27 — "I found that he had committed nothing worthy of death... Of whom I have no certain thing to write... it seemeth to me unreasonable to send a prisoner, and not withal to signify the crimes." The governor''s legal embarrassment is Luke''s theological vindication: no crime exists because Christianity is not criminal.'),
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 4, 'What is the dramatic significance of Paul''s hearing before Agrippa being held "with great pomp" (25:23)?', 'The hearing is staged in the audience chamber with military commanders and prominent men — maximum secular splendour. Yet the true power dynamic is inverted: the prisoner Paul possesses the truth that kings and governors need. Luke contrasts worldly "pomp" (phantasia = display/show) with the reality of the gospel. The one in chains is freer than the ones on thrones', 'The pomp honoured Paul', 'Agrippa was being humble', 'The setting was unimportant to Luke', 'a', 'Acts 25:23 — "Agrippa was come, and Bernice, with great pomp (phantasia)." The Greek word "phantasia" means show/display — the same root as "phantom." The contrast is deliberate: outward show vs. inward reality. The chained apostle has what the crowned king lacks — truth, hope, and freedom.'),
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 5, 'How does Acts 25 fulfil Jesus'' prediction in Luke 21:12-13 and Acts 9:15?', 'Jesus predicted: "They shall bring you before kings and rulers for my name''s sake. And it shall turn to you for a testimony" (Luke 21:12-13). Acts 9:15: Paul would "bear my name before the Gentiles, and kings." Now Paul stands before a king (Agrippa), governors (Felix, Festus), and will eventually reach the emperor. The trials are not obstacles but platforms — persecution becomes proclamation', 'These predictions were not fulfilled', 'Only the Agrippa hearing counts', 'Paul never appeared before a king', 'a', 'Acts 25 — Paul before Festus (governor) and Agrippa (king) = Luke 21:12-13 and Acts 9:15 fulfilled. The trial is transformed from prosecution into pulpit. Every legal proceeding in chapters 22-26 is simultaneously a gospel presentation. Opposition creates opportunities for witness before the powerful.'),
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 6, 'What does Festus''s behaviour — wanting to "do the Jews a pleasure" by sending Paul to Jerusalem (25:9) — reveal about political corruption and its limits?', 'Like Felix before him (24:27), Festus prioritises political expediency over justice. Yet Paul''s appeal to Caesar removes the case from corrupt provincial politics. God uses legal rights to protect against political manipulation. Luke shows that while Roman justice is imperfect (governors are corruptible), the system itself provides safeguards (the right of appeal) that serve God''s purposes', 'Festus was acting justly', 'Paul had no legal options', 'Roman justice was entirely corrupt', 'a', 'Acts 25:9 — "Festus, willing to do the Jews a pleasure, answered Paul..." Festus repeats Felix''s error (24:27 — "willing to shew the Jews a pleasure"). Both governors sacrifice justice for political favour. Yet Paul''s appeal to Caesar (a legal right) overrides gubernatorial corruption. God works through imperfect systems.'),
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 7, 'How does the Agrippa-Festus dynamic function in the trial narrative?', 'Festus provides Roman administrative perspective (political charges) while Agrippa provides Jewish religious expertise (theological charges). Together they cover all possible angles of accusation. Yet both find Paul innocent — the Jewish expert and the Roman administrator agree. Luke uses their complementary competencies to provide comprehensive vindication', 'Only Festus was involved in the case', 'Agrippa was hostile to Paul', 'Their perspectives were identical', 'a', 'Festus: "no crime worthy of death" (25:25). Agrippa: "this man might have been set at liberty" (26:32). The Roman administrator and the Jewish king independently reach the same conclusion: Paul is innocent. Luke builds his case through expert witnesses from both jurisdictions.'),
('Acts', 25, 'adults', 8, 'What is the irony of Festus finding it "unreasonable to send a prisoner, and not withal to signify the crimes" (25:27)?', 'The supreme irony: a Roman governor must send a prisoner to the emperor but cannot explain what crime he committed. The prisoner has been investigated by multiple authorities over multiple years and no charge stands. Paul is a prisoner without a crime — echoing Jesus, who was convicted without guilt (Luke 23:4,14,22). The legal system has become absurd because the "crime" is the gospel', 'There was nothing ironic about the situation', 'Festus easily identified the crimes', 'Paul had committed obvious offences', 'a', 'Acts 25:27 — "It seemeth to me unreasonable to send a prisoner, and not withal to signify the crimes." The governor admits the absurdity: Paul is a prisoner, yet no crime exists. The entire Roman legal apparatus — governors, soldiers, hearings — has been activated for a man whose only offence is proclaiming that a dead man is alive.');

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 26 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 26, 'kids', 1, 'What question did Paul ask King Agrippa about the prophets?', 'King Agrippa, believest thou the prophets? I know that thou believest', 'Do you want to hear a story?', 'Have you ever been to Jerusalem?', 'Can you read the Scriptures?', 'a', 'Acts 26:27 — "King Agrippa, believest thou the prophets? I know that thou believest."'),
('Acts', 26, 'kids', 2, 'What did Paul say Jesus told him to do on the road to Damascus?', 'To be a minister and a witness, and to open people''s eyes so they can turn from darkness to light', 'To go and build a new temple', 'To become a farmer in Galilee', 'To join the Roman army', 'a', 'Acts 26:16-18 — "I have appeared unto thee for this purpose, to make thee a minister and a witness... To open their eyes, and to turn them from darkness to light, and from the power of Satan unto God."'),
('Acts', 26, 'kids', 3, 'What did King Agrippa say to Paul after hearing his story?', 'Almost thou persuadest me to be a Christian', 'I want to be baptised right now', 'I do not believe anything you said', 'You must be sent to prison', 'a', 'Acts 26:28 — "Then Agrippa said unto Paul, Almost thou persuadest me to be a Christian."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 26, 'teens', 1, 'How did Paul describe his former life as a Pharisee?', 'He lived after the strictest sect of the Jewish religion — he was a Pharisee who persecuted the church, imprisoning and punishing believers, and even voted for their death', 'He was a quiet scholar who avoided conflict', 'He was a merchant who traded goods', 'He was a farmer in Galilee', 'a', 'Acts 26:5,9-11 — "After the most straitest sect of our religion I lived a Pharisee... I verily thought with myself, that I ought to do many things contrary to the name of Jesus of Nazareth... I shut up in prison... I punished them oft... and when they were put to death, I gave my voice against them."'),
('Acts', 26, 'teens', 2, 'What was Festus''s reaction when Paul spoke about the resurrection?', 'Festus said with a loud voice "Paul, thou art beside thyself; much learning doth make thee mad"', 'Festus was deeply moved and started crying', 'Festus fell asleep during Paul''s speech', 'Festus agreed with everything Paul said', 'a', 'Acts 26:24 — "And as he thus spake for himself, Festus said with a loud voice, Paul, thou art beside thyself; much learning doth make thee mad."'),
('Acts', 26, 'teens', 3, 'How did Paul respond to Festus''s accusation of madness?', 'I am not mad, most noble Festus; but speak forth the words of truth and soberness — these things were not done in a corner', 'He apologised for being too passionate', 'He stopped speaking entirely', 'He agreed that it sounded crazy', 'a', 'Acts 26:25-26 — "But he said, I am not mad, most noble Festus; but speak forth the words of truth and soberness. For the king knoweth of these things, before whom also I speak freely: for I am persuaded that none of these things are hidden from him; for this thing was not done in a corner."'),
('Acts', 26, 'teens', 4, 'What did Agrippa and Festus agree about Paul after the hearing?', 'This man doeth nothing worthy of death or of bonds — he might have been set at liberty if he had not appealed unto Caesar', 'Paul was guilty of treason', 'Paul should be punished severely', 'Paul needed to stay in prison longer', 'a', 'Acts 26:31-32 — "And when they were gone aside, they talked between themselves, saying, This man doeth nothing worthy of death or of bonds. Then said Agrippa unto Festus, This man might have been set at liberty, if he had not appealed unto Caesar."'),
('Acts', 26, 'teens', 5, 'What did Paul say he wished for everyone who heard him that day?', 'That they might become such as he was, except for his chains — meaning he wished they would all become Christians', 'That they would become rulers of Rome', 'That they would leave Caesarea and travel the world', 'That they would forget everything he said', 'a', 'Acts 26:29 — "I would to God, that not only thou, but also all that hear me this day, were both almost, and altogether such as I am, except these bonds."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 1, 'How does Paul''s third telling of his conversion (Acts 26) differ from the first two, and what does it add?', 'This version adds the most detailed commission from Jesus: "to open their eyes, to turn them from darkness to light, and from the power of Satan unto God" (v.18). It also adds "it is hard for thee to kick against the pricks" (v.14) and omits Ananias''s role entirely — Paul receives his commission directly from Christ. Each retelling emphasises different aspects for the specific audience', 'All three accounts are identical', 'This version contradicts the others', 'The differences indicate fabrication', 'a', 'Acts 26:14-18 — Unique to this account: "kick against the pricks" (v.14, a Greek proverb), the comprehensive commission (v.16-18), the light-darkness/Satan-God framework (v.18). Ananias is omitted because Paul argues before royalty that his authority comes directly from Christ. Each retelling is tailored, not contradictory.'),
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 2, 'What does "it is hard for thee to kick against the pricks" (26:14) mean?', 'The phrase is a Greek proverb about an ox kicking against the sharp goad that drives it — futile resistance against a superior force. Applied to Paul, it means his persecution of the church was futile resistance against God''s sovereign purposes. Paul was fighting against God and harming only himself. The proverb, from Greek literature (Euripides, Aeschylus), shows Jesus speaking in terms Paul''s educated mind would understand', 'Paul was literally kicking something', 'The phrase is a Hebrew expression', 'It means Paul was physically injured', 'a', 'Acts 26:14 — "It is hard for thee to kick against the pricks (kentra)." The goad metaphor (from Euripides'' Bacchae and Aeschylus'' Agamemnon) describes futile resistance against divine power. Jesus uses a Greek idiom for Saul the Hellenised Jew. Paul''s persecution was self-destructive opposition to God''s irresistible purpose.'),
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 3, 'How does Paul''s commission in 26:16-18 summarise the entire mission theology of Acts?', 'The commission contains Acts'' complete mission theology: Paul as "minister and witness" (v.16), sent to open eyes (v.18a), turn from darkness to light (v.18b), from Satan''s power to God (v.18c), offer forgiveness of sins (v.18d), and inheritance among the sanctified by faith (v.18e). Every element — witness, illumination, liberation, forgiveness, inheritance, faith — encapsulates the gospel''s content and method', 'The commission was only about preaching', 'It applied only to Paul personally', 'Mission theology is not found in Acts', 'a', 'Acts 26:16-18 — The commission layers five salvific effects: (1) eyes opened (illumination), (2) darkness → light (epistemological transformation), (3) Satan → God (spiritual liberation), (4) forgiveness of sins (justification), (5) inheritance among the sanctified by faith (adoption/eschatological hope). This is the gospel in miniature.'),
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 4, 'What does Agrippa''s response ("Almost thou persuadest me to be a Christian," 26:28) reveal?', 'Whether sincere or sarcastic (the Greek en oligo is ambiguous — "in a little" = briefly/almost/easily), Agrippa''s response shows the gospel pressing for a decision. Paul''s response treats it as genuine engagement: "I would to God... all were such as I am." Even a possible deflection becomes a gospel opportunity. Agrippa acknowledges the force of Paul''s argument without submitting to it — the tragedy of the unconverted intellectual', 'Agrippa became a Christian', 'The response was purely sarcastic', 'Paul was disappointed by Agrippa''s answer', 'a', 'Acts 26:28-29 — "En oligo" is debated: "in a short time" (you''d make me a Christian quickly) or "with little effort" (you almost persuade me). Either way, Paul seizes it: "I wish all who hear me today were such as I am." Whether Agrippa deflects or nearly yields, Paul turns the moment toward the gospel.'),
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 5, 'What does the verdict "This man might have been set at liberty, if he had not appealed unto Caesar" (26:32) accomplish in Luke''s narrative?', 'It is the climactic vindication: the highest Jewish authority (Agrippa) and the highest Roman authority in Judaea (Festus) agree Paul is innocent. The appeal to Caesar, which seems to prevent release, actually fulfils divine purpose — Paul must reach Rome (23:11). Human innocence and divine necessity intersect: Paul is legally innocent yet divinely bound for Rome', 'The verdict meant Paul was guilty', 'The appeal to Caesar was a mistake', 'Agrippa''s opinion did not matter', 'a', 'Acts 26:31-32 — "This man doeth nothing worthy of death or of bonds." The progression: Lysias (23:29), Felix (24:25 — no verdict but no condemnation), Festus (25:25), Agrippa (26:31-32). Four officials, zero convictions. The appeal to Caesar is not a legal error but a divine vehicle. Innocence and destiny converge.'),
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 6, 'How does Paul''s statement "this thing was not done in a corner" (26:26) function as an apologetic principle?', 'Paul claims the events of the gospel — Jesus'' ministry, death, and resurrection — are public, historical, and verifiable, not private myths or secret mysteries. This is an appeal to the historical nature of Christianity: it is based on events that happened in real places, among real people, in full view of history. Faith is not blind but based on public evidence', 'Paul was speaking about his trial only', 'The gospel was a private matter', 'Paul was referring to his years in hiding', 'a', 'Acts 26:26 — "This thing was not done in a corner." Paul appeals to the public, historical nature of the gospel events. The crucifixion was public (under Pontius Pilate), the resurrection had hundreds of witnesses (1 Corinthians 15:6), and Paul''s own conversion was known throughout the empire. Christianity stakes its claim on history, not mythology.'),
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 7, 'What does Paul''s wish — "except these bonds" (26:29) — reveal about his understanding of suffering and freedom?', 'Paul offers everything he has to Agrippa — his faith, his joy, his calling — but not his chains. This is both pastoral (he would not wish imprisonment on anyone) and deeply theological: Paul''s chains are the cost of discipleship, not the content of the gospel. He is genuinely free despite chains. True freedom is internal (relationship with Christ), not external (absence of chains)', 'Paul was complaining about his imprisonment', 'He wanted Agrippa to also be imprisoned', 'The chains were merely metaphorical', 'a', 'Acts 26:29 — "Both almost, and altogether such as I am, except these bonds." Paul generously offers everything positive and withholds only suffering. Yet the irony is profound: the man in chains is freer than the king on the throne. Paul''s bonds are the evidence of his mission, not its failure.'),
('Acts', 26, 'adults', 8, 'How does Acts 26 represent the climax of Paul''s defence speeches and their collective theological contribution?', 'Acts 26 is the fullest and most theologically developed of Paul''s defence speeches, integrating his biography, Christology, soteriology, and missiology. The progression from ch.22 (Jewish crowd) through ch.24 (Felix) to ch.26 (Agrippa) shows increasing theological depth and wider audience. Together, the speeches demonstrate that the gospel is historically grounded, scripturally rooted, personally transformative, and universally relevant', 'Chapter 26 is the weakest of Paul''s speeches', 'The speeches are repetitive without development', 'Paul never discussed theology in his defences', 'a', 'Acts 26 is the culmination: fuller commission (vv.16-18), stronger prophetic argument (vv.22-23), direct evangelistic appeal (vv.27-29), and comprehensive verdict (vv.31-32). The defence speeches in Acts 22-26 function as Luke''s final theological showcase: Paul the prisoner becomes Paul the preacher, and the courtroom becomes a church.');

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 27–28 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 27 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 27, 'kids', 1, 'What happened to the ship Paul was sailing on to Rome?', 'A terrible storm hit and the ship was wrecked, but everyone on board survived', 'The ship sailed smoothly with no problems', 'Pirates attacked the ship', 'The ship caught fire', 'a', 'Acts 27:41,44 — "And falling into a place where two seas met, they ran the ship aground... And so it came to pass, that they escaped all safe to land."'),
('Acts', 27, 'kids', 2, 'What did an angel tell Paul during the storm?', 'Fear not, Paul — God hath given thee all them that sail with thee. Not one person would be lost', 'Abandon the ship and swim to shore', 'The storm would stop in one hour', 'Only Paul would survive', 'a', 'Acts 27:23-24 — "There stood by me this night the angel of God, whose I am, and whom I serve, Saying, Fear not, Paul; thou must be brought before Caesar: and, lo, God hath given thee all them that sail with thee."'),
('Acts', 27, 'kids', 3, 'How many people were on the ship with Paul?', 'Two hundred and seventy-six souls', 'Twelve people', 'One hundred people', 'Five hundred people', 'a', 'Acts 27:37 — "And we were in all in the ship two hundred threescore and sixteen souls."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 27, 'teens', 1, 'What did Paul warn the sailors about before the storm?', 'He said the voyage would be with hurt and much damage, not only of the ship and cargo, but also of their lives — but they ignored him', 'He told them to take a different route', 'He asked them to wait for a bigger ship', 'He suggested they fly instead of sailing', 'a', 'Acts 27:10 — "Sirs, I perceive that this voyage will be with hurt and much damage, not only of the lading and ship, but also of our lives."'),
('Acts', 27, 'teens', 2, 'How long did the terrible storm last?', 'Fourteen days — for many days neither sun nor stars appeared, and all hope of being saved was taken away', 'Three days', 'One week', 'One month', 'a', 'Acts 27:20,27 — "When neither sun nor stars in many days appeared, and no small tempest lay on us, all hope that we should be saved was then taken away... But when the fourteenth night was come."'),
('Acts', 27, 'teens', 3, 'What did Paul urge the frightened passengers to do?', 'Be of good cheer — he believed God that it would be even as the angel had told him, and not one life would be lost', 'Prepare to die bravely', 'Jump overboard and swim', 'Hide below deck and pray', 'a', 'Acts 27:22,25 — "And now I exhort you to be of good cheer: for there shall be no loss of any man''s life among you, but of the ship... Wherefore, sirs, be of good cheer: for I believe God, that it shall be even as it was told me."'),
('Acts', 27, 'teens', 4, 'What did Paul do before encouraging everyone to eat?', 'He took bread, gave thanks to God in the presence of them all, broke it, and began to eat', 'He asked the captain to prepare a feast', 'He fasted for three more days', 'He divided the food equally himself', 'a', 'Acts 27:35 — "And when he had thus spoken, he took bread, and gave thanks to God in presence of them all: and when he had broken it, he began to eat."'),
('Acts', 27, 'teens', 5, 'How did the passengers reach the shore of Malta after the ship ran aground?', 'Some swam, and the rest held onto boards and broken pieces of the ship — and they all escaped safely to land', 'A rescue boat came for them', 'They walked on a sandbar to the shore', 'Dolphins carried them to safety', 'a', 'Acts 27:44 — "And the rest, some on boards, and some on broken pieces of the ship. And so it came to pass, that they escaped all safe to land."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 1, 'How does the shipwreck narrative function theologically within Luke''s overall argument?', 'The voyage to Rome is the final obstacle between Paul and his divine destiny. The storm tests whether God''s promise (23:11, "thou must bear witness at Rome") will be fulfilled. The angel''s message (27:24) reaffirms divine certainty. The salvation of all 276 passengers because of Paul mirrors Jonah in reverse: Paul''s presence saves, not endangers. God''s sovereign protection operates even in nature''s fury', 'The shipwreck is merely an adventure story', 'It has no theological significance', 'Paul was being punished like Jonah', 'a', 'Acts 27 — The storm tests God''s promise. The angel says: "thou must (dei) be brought before Caesar" (v.24). The divine "must" overrules wind, waves, and human despair. Paul''s faith contrasts with the sailors'' panic. All are saved because of one man — a reversal of Jonah, where all were endangered by one man.'),
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 2, 'What does Paul''s leadership during the storm reveal about the relationship between faith and practical wisdom?', 'Paul combines spiritual confidence (the angel''s promise, v.23-24) with practical wisdom (warning against leaving Fair Havens, v.10; preventing sailors from abandoning ship, v.31; urging everyone to eat, v.34). Faith does not bypass practical action — Paul trusts God''s promise while also making prudent decisions. Spiritual assurance and human responsibility coexist', 'Paul relied solely on miraculous intervention', 'He was passive throughout the storm', 'His practical advice contradicted his faith', 'a', 'Acts 27:10,24,31,34 — Paul warns (practical), trusts the angel (spiritual), prevents abandonment (practical), and encourages eating (practical). He believes "it shall be even as it was told me" (v.25) while actively participating in the survival effort. Faith is not fatalism — it empowers practical action.'),
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 3, 'What is the significance of Paul giving thanks and breaking bread "in presence of them all" (27:35)?', 'Paul''s public thanksgiving before 276 people — most of them pagans — transforms a survival meal into a witness. The language (took bread, gave thanks, broke it) echoes the Eucharist (Luke 22:19) and the Emmaus meal (Luke 24:30). Whether or not it is a formal Lord''s Supper, Paul''s public prayer demonstrates faith and identifies the God who saves', 'Paul was simply being polite', 'The meal had no spiritual dimension', 'Only Christians were present', 'a', 'Acts 27:35-36 — "He took bread, and gave thanks to God in presence of them all: and when he had broken it, he began to eat. Then were they all of good cheer." The Eucharistic echoes (Luke 22:19, 24:30) are unmistakable. Paul''s public thanksgiving before pagans turns a crisis meal into an act of witness. Their subsequent encouragement shows the impact.'),
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 4, 'How does Luke''s detailed nautical account serve his purposes as a historian?', 'The "we" narrative provides eyewitness detail: specific harbours (Fair Havens, Phoenix), wind names (Euroclydon/Euraquilo), sailing techniques (undergirding the ship, striking sail, casting anchors), and exact numbers (276 passengers, 14 days). This maritime precision demonstrates Luke''s reliability as a historian and provides verisimilitude that anchors the theological narrative in concrete reality', 'The nautical details are fictional', 'Luke had no sailing knowledge', 'The details are irrelevant filler', 'a', 'Acts 27 — Professional nautical terminology throughout: "under lee of" (v.4,7), "undergirding" (hypozonnyntes, v.17), "sounded" (v.28), "four anchors out of the stern" (v.29). Maritime historians confirm Luke''s accuracy. This detail serves historiography (trustworthy record) and theology (God works in the real, physical world).'),
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 5, 'What does the soldiers'' plan to kill the prisoners (27:42) and the centurion''s intervention (27:43) reveal?', 'Roman soldiers were personally liable for escaped prisoners (cf. Acts 12:19). Their plan to kill prisoners was standard military protocol. The centurion''s intervention — "willing to save Paul" — shows Paul had earned his captor''s respect. God uses the centurion''s personal regard for Paul to save all the prisoners. Individual relationships become instruments of providential protection', 'The soldiers were being cruel without reason', 'The centurion was a secret Christian', 'Paul had bribed the centurion', 'a', 'Acts 27:42-43 — "The soldiers'' counsel was to kill the prisoners, lest any of them should swim out, and escape. But the centurion, willing to save Paul, kept them from their purpose." The centurion''s personal respect for Paul (built throughout the voyage) overrides military protocol. Human relationships become channels of divine protection.'),
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 6, 'How does the phrase "God hath given thee all them that sail with thee" (27:24) illustrate the concept of blessing through association?', 'Because of Paul — God''s servant — all 276 passengers are spared. This echoes the pattern of blessing through God''s chosen: Potiphar''s house blessed because of Joseph (Genesis 39:5), Laban blessed because of Jacob (Genesis 30:27). The presence of a faithful believer becomes a source of protection for others. Paul''s relationship with God has communal, not just individual, consequences', 'Only Paul was protected', 'The others survived by luck', 'Paul had no influence on the outcome', 'a', 'Acts 27:24 — "God hath given thee all them that sail with thee." The 275 others are saved because of one man''s relationship with God. This is the Abrahamic blessing principle (Genesis 12:3) in miniature: through God''s servant, others are blessed. Paul is a living illustration of the promise that blessing flows through God''s people.'),
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 7, 'What does the narrative progression from "all hope that we should be saved was taken away" (27:20) to "they escaped all safe to land" (27:44) demonstrate?', 'The progression from total despair to complete salvation mirrors the gospel pattern: death to resurrection, hopelessness to deliverance. Luke crafts the narrative so that human resources are exhausted before divine intervention is revealed. The storm strips away every human support (cargo, tackle, food, hope) until only God''s promise remains — and that promise proves sufficient', 'The outcome was predictable', 'No one actually lost hope', 'The storm was mild', 'a', 'Acts 27:20,44 — The narrative arc: hope abandoned (v.20) → divine promise (v.24) → human obedience (v.31-36) → complete salvation (v.44). Luke structures the story as a parable of salvation: when all human hope is exhausted, God''s word alone sustains. The 14-day descent into despair makes the rescue all the more dramatic and God-glorifying.'),
('Acts', 27, 'adults', 8, 'How does Paul''s transformation from prisoner to de facto leader of the ship illustrate a key theme of Acts?', 'Throughout the voyage, Paul progressively assumes leadership: advising the centurion (v.10), receiving divine revelation (v.23-24), preventing the sailors'' escape (v.31), encouraging the crew (v.34-36), and directing the meal (v.35). The prisoner becomes the captain, the accused becomes the authority. This reversal illustrates Acts'' consistent theme: the gospel inverts power structures — the weak become strong, the bound become free', 'Paul remained passive throughout', 'The centurion was the only leader', 'Paul''s leadership was accidental', 'a', 'Paul''s authority grows throughout chapter 27: ignored advisor (v.11) → prophetic voice (v.24) → practical commander (v.31) → spiritual leader (v.35). The prisoner is the only person on board with access to divine knowledge and genuine hope. Acts consistently shows worldly power inverted by spiritual authority.');

-- ═══ Acts Chapter 28 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Acts', 28, 'kids', 1, 'What happened when Paul was bitten by a poisonous snake on the island of Malta?', 'He shook the snake off into the fire and was not hurt at all', 'He got very sick for many days', 'A doctor had to give him medicine', 'He was rushed to the hospital', 'a', 'Acts 28:5 — "And he shook off the beast into the fire, and felt no harm."'),
('Acts', 28, 'kids', 2, 'What did Paul do for the father of Publius, the chief man of the island?', 'He prayed and laid his hands on him, and the man was healed of his fever and bloody flux', 'He gave him money for medicine', 'He brought him food and water', 'He told him a bedtime story', 'a', 'Acts 28:8 — "And it came to pass, that the father of Publius lay sick of a fever and of a bloody flux: to whom Paul entered in, and prayed, and laid his hands on him, and healed him."'),
('Acts', 28, 'kids', 3, 'What did Paul do when he finally arrived in Rome?', 'He lived in his own rented house for two years, preaching the kingdom of God and teaching about the Lord Jesus Christ to everyone who came to see him', 'He was thrown in a dark dungeon', 'He escaped and sailed back to Jerusalem', 'He became a Roman senator', 'a', 'Acts 28:30-31 — "And Paul dwelt two whole years in his own hired house, and received all that came in unto him, Preaching the kingdom of God, and teaching those things which concern the Lord Jesus Christ, with all confidence, no man forbidding him."'),
-- Teens
('Acts', 28, 'teens', 1, 'What did the people of Malta think when the snake bit Paul?', 'First they thought he was a murderer being punished by justice, but when he did not die they changed their minds and said he was a god', 'They thought he was a fisherman', 'They were not concerned about the snake', 'They thought snakes were harmless', 'a', 'Acts 28:4,6 — "No doubt this man is a murderer, whom, though he hath escaped the sea, yet vengeance suffereth not to live... they changed their minds, and said that he was a god."'),
('Acts', 28, 'teens', 2, 'What happened after Paul healed Publius''s father?', 'Others on the island who had diseases also came and were healed', 'Paul was arrested by the island rulers', 'Nothing else happened on the island', 'The islanders refused to believe', 'a', 'Acts 28:9 — "So when this was done, others also, which had diseases in the island, came, and were healed."'),
('Acts', 28, 'teens', 3, 'What did Paul tell the Jewish leaders in Rome?', 'He explained his case — that he had done nothing against the Jewish people or customs, but was a prisoner because of the hope of Israel', 'He asked them to help him escape', 'He told them to convert to Christianity or face judgment', 'He refused to speak with any Jews', 'a', 'Acts 28:17,20 — "I have committed nothing against the people, or customs of our fathers... For the hope of Israel I am bound with this chain."'),
('Acts', 28, 'teens', 4, 'How did the Jewish leaders in Rome respond to Paul''s preaching?', 'Some believed the things which were spoken, and some believed not — they disagreed among themselves', 'They all believed immediately', 'They all rejected Paul completely', 'They asked Paul to leave Rome', 'a', 'Acts 28:24-25 — "And some believed the things which were spoken, and some believed not. And when they agreed not among themselves, they departed."'),
('Acts', 28, 'teens', 5, 'What was the last thing Paul said to the Jewish leaders who rejected his message?', 'The salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles, and they will hear it — quoting Isaiah about people with dull ears and closed eyes', 'I will never speak to Jews again', 'God has given up on the Jewish people', 'I am returning to Jerusalem immediately', 'a', 'Acts 28:28 — "Be it known therefore unto you, that the salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles, and that they will hear it."'),
-- Adults
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 1, 'What does the Malta snake incident (28:3-6) symbolically represent in Luke''s narrative?', 'The viper attack and Paul''s immunity echoes Jesus'' promise to His disciples (Mark 16:18, Luke 10:19). It also demonstrates divine protection of God''s messenger — Paul must reach Rome, so even a deadly serpent cannot stop him. The Maltese reaction (murderer → god) echoes the Lystra pattern (human → divine attribution), showing that pagans interpret divine power through their own categories', 'The snake was not actually venomous', 'The incident has no symbolic meaning', 'Paul used an antidote', 'a', 'Acts 28:3-6 — Paul survives a viper bite without harm. The Maltese interpret this through their pagan justice-theology: first he is a murderer (justice strikes), then a god (divine immunity). Luke shows both the reality of divine protection and the inadequacy of pagan interpretation. Paul neither dies nor becomes a god — he is God''s protected servant.'),
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 2, 'How does Paul''s healing ministry on Malta (28:7-9) mirror Jesus'' ministry and earlier apostolic ministry?', 'Paul prays, lays on hands, and heals — the same pattern as Jesus (Luke 4:40) and Peter (Acts 9:34,40). The healing of "all the diseases" on the island echoes Jesus'' comprehensive healing ministry. Luke shows that the same power that operated through Jesus and Peter operates through Paul at the end of Acts — the chain of authority is unbroken from Christ through the apostles', 'Paul used medicine, not prayer', 'Healings only occurred in Jerusalem', 'Malta''s healings were different from Jesus''', 'a', 'Acts 28:8 — "Paul entered in, and prayed, and laid his hands on him, and healed him." The pattern (prayer + laying on of hands + healing) replicates Jesus (Luke 4:40) and Peter (Acts 9:17,34). Luke closes his narrative as he began it: with the power of God healing through His servants.'),
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 3, 'What does Paul''s quotation of Isaiah 6:9-10 (28:26-27) signify as the final Old Testament citation in Acts?', 'Isaiah 6:9-10 — about hearing without understanding and seeing without perceiving — is the most quoted OT passage in the NT (used by Jesus in all four Gospels). Paul''s citation at the end of Acts declares that Jewish rejection of the gospel fulfils the same prophetic pattern as Israel''s rejection of Isaiah''s message. Jewish unbelief is tragic but scripturally anticipated', 'Paul was cursing the Jewish people', 'Isaiah 6 has no connection to the gospel', 'This was a minor quotation with no significance', 'a', 'Acts 28:26-27 — Isaiah 6:9-10 appears in Matthew 13:14-15, Mark 4:12, Luke 8:10, John 12:40, Romans 11:8, and now Acts 28:26-27. Its placement as Acts'' final OT citation is deliberate: Jewish unbelief fulfils Scripture. Yet Paul does not pronounce final rejection — Isaiah 6 is followed by a remnant promise (Isaiah 6:13).'),
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 4, 'What is the significance of "the salvation of God is sent unto the Gentiles, and they will hear it" (28:28) as the third and final turning-to-Gentiles declaration?', 'This is the third "turning to Gentiles" declaration (after 13:46 and 18:6), and its placement at Acts'' end gives it climactic force. It is not a final rejection of Jews (Paul still meets with Jewish leaders) but a programmatic statement: the gospel''s primary audience has shifted to Gentiles. Acts ends as it began — with a statement of universal mission (1:8). The gospel has reached "the uttermost part of the earth" (Rome)', 'Paul permanently rejected all Jews', 'This was the first time Paul turned to Gentiles', 'The Gentile mission was secondary', 'a', 'Acts 28:28 — The three declarations (13:46, 18:6, 28:28) create a structural rhythm: Jewish rejection → Gentile expansion. The final declaration at Rome (the empire''s centre) brings Acts 1:8 to fulfilment. The gospel has moved from Jerusalem to Rome, from Jews to Gentiles, from temple to house — and none of this contradicts the original promise.'),
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 5, 'Why does Acts end with Paul under house arrest rather than with his trial or death?', 'Luke''s purpose was not biographical (Paul''s life story) but theological (the gospel''s unstoppable advance). The open ending shows the gospel still advancing: Paul "preaching the kingdom of God... with all confidence, no man forbidding him." The final words "unhindered" (akolutos) are the book''s theological conclusion: despite chains, the word is free. Acts ends not with a period but a colon — the mission continues', 'Luke planned a third volume', 'Luke did not know what happened next', 'Paul''s trial was unimportant', 'a', 'Acts 28:30-31 — The book ends with Paul in chains but the gospel "unhindered" (akolutos). This paradox is Luke''s final theological statement: human imprisonment cannot imprison the word. The open ending invites the reader to continue the mission. Acts has no ending because the church''s story has no ending.'),
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 6, 'What does "preaching the kingdom of God, and teaching those things which concern the Lord Jesus Christ" (28:31) accomplish as Acts'' final statement?', 'The double phrase combines the whole message of Acts: "the kingdom of God" (Jesus'' message, connecting to Luke''s Gospel) and "the Lord Jesus Christ" (the apostolic kerygma, the content of Acts). The two together show continuity between Jesus'' preaching and the church''s preaching. The final word in Greek is "akolutos" (unhindered) — the gospel is free even when its preacher is not', 'It is merely a summary with no special significance', 'Only the kingdom of God was preached', 'Only Jesus Christ was taught', 'a', 'Acts 28:31 — "Kingdom of God" connects to Jesus'' own preaching (Acts 1:3). "Lord Jesus Christ" is the full apostolic confession. Together they bridge the Gospels and Acts, Jesus'' ministry and the church''s ministry. The final word "akolutos" (unhindered/without prohibition) is the triumphant note: nothing — not Rome, not chains, not storm, not snake — can stop the gospel.'),
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 7, 'How does the phrase "for the hope of Israel I am bound with this chain" (28:20) encapsulate Paul''s entire defence throughout Acts?', 'Paul''s consistent claim is that Christianity is not a departure from Judaism but its fulfilment. "The hope of Israel" is the resurrection (23:6, 24:15, 26:6-8) — the very hope that drove Israel''s faith. Paul''s chains are evidence not of heterodoxy but of orthodoxy: he suffers for believing what the prophets promised. The gospel is the hope of Israel realised, not abandoned', 'Paul was referring to a political hope', 'The hope of Israel was irrelevant to his chains', 'Paul was trying to gain Jewish sympathy falsely', 'a', 'Acts 28:20 — "For the hope of Israel I am bound with this chain." This phrase crystallises Paul''s apologetic across all his speeches: his imprisonment results from believing the very thing Israel''s Scriptures promised. The resurrection is "the hope of Israel" — Christianity is Judaism fulfilled. Paul''s chains testify to his faithfulness, not his betrayal.'),
('Acts', 28, 'adults', 8, 'How does the ending of Acts complete the programmatic statement of Acts 1:8?', 'Acts 1:8 promised witness in Jerusalem, Judaea, Samaria, and the uttermost part of the earth. By Acts 28, the gospel has reached Rome — the centre of the known world. Jerusalem (ch.1-7), Judaea/Samaria (ch.8-12), and the ends of the earth (ch.13-28) are complete. Paul preaches "with all confidence, no man forbidding him" in the empire''s capital. The Spirit''s mission, announced in chapter 1, is accomplished in chapter 28', 'Acts 1:8 was never fulfilled', 'Only Jerusalem was reached', 'Rome was not significant', 'a', 'Acts 28:30-31 fulfils 1:8 — The gospel stands in Rome, the empire''s heart. The geographic trajectory (Jerusalem → Judaea → Samaria → ends of the earth) is complete. But the open ending (no formal conclusion) implies the mission continues beyond Acts: every generation is called to extend the witness further. Acts 1:8 is both fulfilled and ongoing.');
